"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Job chapters 36–38
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-job-36-38.py
Verses: ch36×33 + ch37×24 + ch38×41 = 98

Key Christological notes:
- ch36: Elihu's closing speech. v10 the Servant's opened ear (Isa 50:4-5; Heb 5:8);
  v15 rescue through affliction (Isa 53:4-5; 1 Pet 2:24); v22 Christ as incomparable
  Teacher (John 13:13; Isa 30:20; John 14:26); vv27-33 creation governance by Christ.
- ch37: Storm theophany. v3 lightning like Christ's return (Matt 24:27); v4 Christ's
  thunderous voice (Rev 1:15; 19:6); v6 commanding elements (Mark 4:39); v22 approach
  from the north (Rev 4:3; 21:11).
- ch38: YHWH speaks from the whirlwind — the first YHWH since the prose frame. Every
  cosmogonic question is answered by Christ's pre-existence. v4 Heb 1:10 quotes Ps
  102:25 of Christ; v6 the cornerstone of creation = Christ (1 Pet 2:6; Eph 2:20); v7
  sons of God at creation (Col 1:16; Rev 5:11-12); v11 Christ stills the sea (Mark
  4:39); v17 gates of death (Rev 1:18); v36 wisdom in the hidden self (1 Cor 1:24,30).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOB3638 = {
  "36": {
    "1": "<p>The theme: Elihu's fourth speech continues toward its meteorological climax. Christologically, the speech functions as the human ceiling of wisdom-speech — the most eloquent human defender of divine providence — whose insufficiency establishes the need for the divine Word himself. Col 2:3 'in him [Christ] are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' is the answer to all that Elihu approximates but cannot supply.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theme: 'Bear with me a little longer' — the patience Elihu requests is a Christological virtue. Jas 5:7-11 uses Job's own patience as an example before pointing to 'the Lord's compassion and mercy' (v11). Christ himself is the model of patience under suffering: 1 Pet 2:23 'when they hurled their insults at him, he did not retaliate; when he suffered, he made no threats. Instead, he entrusted himself to him who judges justly.'</p>",
    "3": "<p>A revelation of God: 'I will ascribe righteousness (ṣeḏeq) to my Maker.' The assignment of righteousness to God is the ground of Paul's theology: Rom 3:25-26 God demonstrated his righteousness 'so as to be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus.' The divine righteousness that Elihu praises is the righteousness that the NT presents as fully demonstrated at the cross.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: Elihu claims to be 'complete in knowledge' — a claim the divine speeches implicitly evaluate. Col 2:3 'in Christ are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge' is the NT's identification of true completeness of knowledge: it is not a human attribute but a person, available to those who are 'in Christ.'</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: 'God is mighty and despises no one' — the combination of omnipotence and equal regard. Jesus enacts this combination throughout his ministry: the powerful Son of God who 'has compassion on the crowds' (Matt 9:36), who does not despise 'one of these little ones' (Matt 18:10), and who declares 'the one who comes to me I will never drive away' (John 6:37).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He does not keep the wicked alive, but gives justice to the poor (ʿăniyyîm).' Christ's ministry specifically fulfills this: Luke 4:18 'he has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor'; Matt 5:3 'blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.' The divine justice for the poor is enacted in the Incarnation — God taking the side of the least.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He does not take his eyes off the righteous; he seats them on the throne with kings and exalts them forever.' The eschatological seating with kings is the promise Christ makes: Rev 3:21 'to the one who is victorious, I will give the right to sit with me on my throne, just as I was victorious and sat down with my Father on his throne.' The exaltation 'forever' (lāneṣaḥ) anticipates the eternal reign of Rev 22:5.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A revelation of God: 'if they are bound in chains, caught in ropes of affliction' — the divine permission of suffering for the righteous. Heb 12:5-11 (the 'discipline' passage quoting Prov 3:11-12) establishes the same principle: the Father disciplines those he loves. Christ himself is 'the author and perfecter of faith' who 'for the joy set before him endured the cross' (Heb 12:2), the supreme demonstration of discipline producing perfection.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: 'He shows them what they have done and their transgressions — that they have acted arrogantly.' Divine disclosure of sin's nature is the work of the Holy Spirit whom Christ sends: John 16:8 'when he comes, he will prove the world to be in the wrong about sin and righteousness and judgment.' Conviction of sin is a gift, not condemnation — it opens the way to the mercy Christ provides.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: 'He opens their ears (gilāh ʾāzĕnām) to correction.' This ear-opening formula is the prophetic revelation formula of Isa 50:4-5: 'the Sovereign LORD has given me a well-instructed tongue... he wakens me morning by morning; he wakens my ear to listen like one being instructed. The Sovereign LORD has opened my ears.' This is the Servant's description of his own daily ear-opening by God. Heb 5:8 'although he was a Son, he learned obedience from what he suffered' — Christ is the Servant whose ear was opened daily for suffering-instruction.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The theme: 'If they listen and serve him, they will complete their days in prosperity.' The condition-promise structure here is not mere retribution but covenant — the relationship between obedience and flourishing that Christ establishes under grace: John 15:10-11 'if you keep my commands, you will remain in my love... I have told you this so that my joy may be in you and that your joy may be complete.'</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: 'But if they do not listen, they will perish by the sword and die without ever understanding.' The epistemic and physical death of the unresponsive is the consistent OT two-ways teaching. Christ intensifies this: John 8:24 'if you do not believe that I am he, you will indeed die in your sins.' The perishing without understanding is the condition that Christ's teaching addresses.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: 'The godless store resentment; they do not cry to God when he binds them.' The failure to pray in affliction is the mark of the godless. Christ teaches the opposite posture: Luke 18:1 'they should always pray and not give up'; Matt 26:39-44 (Christ prays three times in Gethsemane). The continual prayer in extremity is the model Christ exemplifies and commends.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: 'They die young, and their life ends among the cult prostitutes.' The premature death associated with moral dissolution is the negative image of what Christ redeems. 1 Cor 6:15-20 addresses the cult-prostitute connection directly in the NT, applying Christ's redemption precisely to sexual sin: 'you were bought at a price; therefore honor God with your bodies' (v20).</p>",
    "15": "<p>A type: 'But he rescues the afflicted through their suffering (ʿōnî) and opens their ears through oppression.' The rescue that comes through suffering rather than around it is fulfilled in Christ: Isa 53:4-5 'surely he took up our pain and bore our suffering... by his wounds we are healed'; 1 Pet 2:24 'he himself bore our sins in his body on the cross... by his wounds you have been healed.' The rescue is precisely through, not despite, the affliction — the cross as God's method of salvation.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He was drawing you from the jaws of distress into a broad place.' The broad place (rĕḥāḇāh) of divine rescue appears throughout the rescue Psalms (Ps 18:19; 31:8; 118:5). Christ's resurrection is the ultimate broad-place rescue: 'you have come to Mount Zion, to the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem' (Heb 12:22) — the spaciousness of God's eschatological city replacing the narrow distress of judgment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The theme: 'But now you are full of the judgment due the wicked.' Elihu sees judgment-signs in Job's suffering. Christ takes on himself 'the judgment due the wicked' in its full weight: 2 Cor 5:21 'God made him who had no sin to be sin for us.' The judgment that falls on the innocent man — at Calvary as at Job's ash-heap — is the mechanism of the world's rescue.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theme: 'Beware that anger does not lead you into scoffing.' The danger of bitterness under suffering becoming theological mockery is a real spiritual risk. Heb 12:15 'see to it that no one misses the grace of God and that no bitter root grows up to cause trouble and defile many.' Christ's grace is the remedy for the bitterness that affliction can generate.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The theme: 'Will your wealth hold you in distress?' The insufficiency of material resources before divine judgment is the consistent wisdom teaching. 1 Pet 1:18-19 'you know that it was not with perishable things such as silver or gold that you were redeemed... but with the precious blood of Christ, a lamb without blemish or defect.' What wealth cannot purchase, Christ's blood accomplishes.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: 'Do not long for the night' — the warning against desiring death as escape. Christ transforms the relationship to death: Phil 1:21-23 'for me, to live is Christ and to die is gain... I desire to depart and be with Christ, which is better by far.' The death that Job's culture dreads and that Paul desires is a transformed death — not escape but entrance into Christ's presence.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The theme: 'Be careful not to turn toward evil, for this is what you have been choosing over enduring affliction.' The temptation to resolve suffering through sin rather than through trust is precisely what Christ resisted in the wilderness temptations (Matt 4:1-11) and in Gethsemane ('yet not as I will, but as you will,' Matt 26:39). The faithful endurance of affliction without turning to evil is the path Christ models.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A type: 'Behold, God is exalted in his power; who is a teacher (môreh) like him?' The divine teacher-title is fulfilled in Christ. John 13:13-14 'you call me Teacher and Lord, and rightly so, for that is what I am.' Isa 30:20 'your Teacher will no longer hide himself; your eyes will see your Teacher' — an eschatological promise that Jesus's disciples see fulfilled in the Incarnation. John 14:26 the Spirit 'will teach you all things and will remind you of everything I have said to you.'</p>",
    "23": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who has prescribed his path for him? Who can say, You have done wrong?' The unchallengeable divine sovereignty is the same that Paul cites in Rom 11:34 (quoting Isa 40:13: 'who has known the mind of the Lord?') and 1 Cor 2:16 ('who has known the mind of the Lord so as to instruct him? But we have the mind of Christ'). The unanswerable divine freedom is accessible through Christ's revealed mind.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The theme: 'Remember to extol his work, which people have sung about through the ages.' The universal hymnic tradition of praising divine works is what the NT church inherits and extends: Rev 5:9-14 the new song before the Lamb; Rev 15:3-4 the song of Moses and the Lamb. Christ's redemption is the work that all ages will sing about — the consummate work that surpasses all previous works.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A revelation of God: 'All people have seen it; everyone looks at it from a distance.' The universal visibility of divine works is the premise of natural theology: Rom 1:19-20 'since the creation of the world God's invisible qualities — his eternal power and divine nature — have been clearly seen.' But the 'from a distance' acknowledges epistemic limit — the distance is bridged only in Christ (Eph 2:13 'you who once were far away have been brought near by the blood of Christ').</p>",
    "26": "<p>A revelation of God: 'God is great, beyond knowing (lōʾ-nēḏāʿ); the number of his years cannot be counted.' The divine incomprehensibility and eternity are what the NT applies to Christ: Heb 13:8 'Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever'; Rev 1:8 'I am the Alpha and Omega... who is, and who was, and who is to come, the Almighty.' 1 Tim 6:16 'who alone is immortal and who lives in unapproachable light' — the unapproachable eternity enters approachable human flesh in the Incarnation.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A revelation of God: 'For he draws up the drops of water; they distill as rain from the mist.' The hydrological cycle as divine governance. Col 1:17 'in him all things hold together' — the routine mechanics of weather are part of the 'all things' that Christ upholds. Heb 1:3 'sustaining all things by his powerful word': the meteorological cycle is sustained word by word.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Which the clouds pour down and drop on people in abundance.' The distributive providence of rain. Matt 5:45 'he causes his sun to rise on the evil and the good, and sends rain on the righteous and the unrighteous' — Jesus cites rain distribution as evidence of the Father's non-discriminating generosity, the ground for loving enemies. The same rain is now evidence of Christ-the-Creator's ongoing provision.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Can anyone understand the spreading of the clouds or the thunder from his canopy (śûkkāh)?' The divine sukkah (canopy/booth) as the vehicle of thunderstorm theophany. Rev 7:15 'he who sits on the throne will shelter them with his presence (σκηνώσει ἐπ᾽ αὐτούς)' — the same śukkāh/σκηνή vocabulary; Christ's permanent shelter replaces the temporary cloud canopy.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He scatters his lightning around him and covers the depths of the sea.' The global reach of divine lightning. Ps 97:4 'his lightning lights up the world; the earth sees and trembles.' The same Ps 97 is about the LORD's coming to judge: applied to Christ's return in Rev 1:7 and 19:11-16. The lightning that 'lights up the world' is now the Son of Man whose coming is 'like lightning from east to west' (Matt 24:27).</p>",
    "31": "<p>A revelation of God: 'For by these he governs peoples and provides food in abundance.' The dual governance of rain — both judgment and provision. Matt 6:11 'give us today our daily bread' — Christ teaches prayer for the daily provision that God gives through rain. Rev 11:6 (the two witnesses who 'have power to shut up the heavens so that it will not rain') shows the same governance continuing eschatologically.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He covers his hands with the lightning and commands it to strike its mark.' The lightning wielded by divine hands. Rev 4:5 'from the throne came flashes of lightning, rumblings and peals of thunder' — the same meteorological signs around the heavenly throne where Christ sits (Rev 5:6-7). The hands that command lightning are the same hands that bear the marks of the nails (John 20:25-27).</p>",
    "33": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Its thunder announces his presence.' The meteorological announcement of divine approach connects to the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:16-19) and anticipates the eschatological theophany. 1 Thess 4:16 'the Lord himself will come down from heaven, with a loud command, with the voice of the archangel and with the trumpet call of God' — the coming of Christ announced with thunder-level acoustic power.</p>"
  },
  "37": {
    "1": "<p>A revelation of God: 'At this my heart trembles and leaps from its place.' The physical response to theophanic approach is the universal human response to divine presence. Rev 1:17 'when I saw him, I fell at his feet as though dead' — John's response to the glorified Christ. The trembling that Elihu describes before the approaching storm is what believers will experience before the returning Christ; the difference is that Christ says to the trembling: 'Do not be afraid' (Rev 1:17).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Listen carefully to the roar of his voice (bĕrōgez qōlô) and the rumble that goes out from his mouth.' John 12:28-29: when the Father speaks from heaven, the crowd says it thundered. Rev 1:15 the glorified Christ's voice is 'like the sound of rushing waters'; Rev 19:6 the sound of the great multitude is 'like the roar of rushing waters and like loud peals of thunder.' The divine voice that Elihu hears in the storm is the same voice John hears from the exalted Christ.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A shadow: 'He sends it under the whole sky, and his lightning to the ends of the earth.' The global reach of divine lightning prepares for Matt 24:27: 'for as lightning that comes from the east is visible even in the west, so will be the coming of the Son of Man.' The lightning of creation-governance becomes the lightning of the Second Coming — the same Creator who governs through storms will return with theophanic power.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He thunders in his majestic voice (bĕqôl gĕʾônô).' The voice of divine majesty. Rev 1:15 'his voice was like the sound of rushing waters'; Rev 19:1 'a great multitude in heaven shouting... salvation and glory and power belong to our God.' The majestic voice that Elihu hears in the storm is ultimately the voice of Christ — the Word whose voice is the instrument of creation (Heb 1:2 'through whom also he made the universe') and judgment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: 'God thunders astoundingly with his voice; he does great things beyond our understanding (wĕlōʾ nēḏāʿ).' The incomprehensible works of God. 1 Cor 2:9 'no eye has seen, no ear has heard, no human mind has conceived what God has prepared for those who love him — but God has revealed it to us by his Spirit.' The wonders beyond understanding are revealed through Christ (Col 2:2-3) and accessible to those who have 'the mind of Christ' (1 Cor 2:16).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A revelation of God: 'For he says to the snow: Fall upon the earth.' The divine command to meteorological phenomena. Mark 4:39 Jesus 'rebuked the wind and said to the waves, Quiet! Be still! And the wind died down and it was completely calm.' The disciples ask: 'Who is this? Even the wind and the waves obey him!' — the answer is: the Creator who gave the commands Elihu now describes. Christ speaks to weather because he is the one who originally commanded weather into existence.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He seals the hand of every person so that all humanity may perceive his work.' The divine governance that stops human activity to create attentional space for perceiving God. John 6:44 'no one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draws them' — the Father's sealing of human activity is his drawing-work, creating the receptivity for recognizing the Son. Acts 2:2-4 the Pentecost wind (the same meteorological vocabulary) seals a new community for the perception of Christ's work.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: 'Then the wild animals go into their dens and stay in their lairs.' The ordered response of creation to divine weather is evidence that creation 'knows its place.' The NT applies this creaturely knowledge to the disciples: John 10:27 'my sheep listen to my voice; I know them, and they follow me.' The animal that responds instinctively to the divine storm is the type of the believer who responds to Christ's voice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: 'From the south comes the whirlwind (sûp̄āh).' The whirlwind that Elihu announces is the same form (sĕʿārāh) from which YHWH will answer in 38:1. Acts 2:2 'suddenly a sound like the blowing of a violent wind came from heaven and filled the whole house' — the Pentecost wind that announces the presence and work of the Holy Spirit whom Christ sends (John 15:26) is the NT theophanic wind.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A revelation of God: 'By the breath of God (mĕnišmaṯ-ʾēl) ice is formed.' The divine breath that creates. John 20:22 'he breathed on them and said, Receive the Holy Spirit' — the risen Christ breathes the Spirit into his disciples, the new-creation counterpart to the creation breath of Gen 2:7. The breath that forms ice in winter forms new life in resurrection — both are the activity of the same Spirit.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He loads the clouds with moisture and scatters his lightning-cloud.' The meteorological logistics as ongoing divine governance. Heb 1:3 'sustaining all things by his powerful word' — the Christ who sustains creation does so word by word, including the loading of clouds with precisely the moisture needed. Col 1:17 'in him all things hold together' means the weather held together in Christ.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A revelation of God: 'It turns in every direction by his guidance (bĕtaḥbûlōṯāyw).' The nautical steering-metaphor for divine providence. Eph 1:11 'having been predestined according to the plan of him who works out everything in conformity with the purpose of his will' — the same exhaustive navigational sovereignty that Elihu ascribes to storm-governance, Paul ascribes to the providential governance of salvation history in Christ.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He brings it whether as discipline (lĕšēbeṭ), for his land's sake, or as steadfast love (lĕḥeseḏ).' The three-way purpose of divine storms — discipline, provision, and love — is applied by Paul to all things: Rom 8:28 'in all things God works for the good of those who love him.' The same providential logic that Elihu finds in weather, Paul finds in all circumstances for those in Christ.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Listen to this, Job; stop and consider (hiṯbônān) the wondrous works of God.' The contemplative arrest — the call to stop and perceive. Ps 46:10 'be still and know that I am God.' Christ issues the same invitation: Matt 11:28-29 'come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you and learn from me.' The 'stop and consider' becomes 'come and rest' in Christ.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: 'Do you know how God arranged these things and caused the lightning in his cloud to flash?' The epistemic gap between creature and Creator. 1 Cor 13:12 'for now we see only a reflection as in a mirror; then we shall see face to face. Now I know in part; then I shall know fully, even as I am fully known.' The partial knowledge that Elihu acknowledges will be resolved in the eschatological knowledge of seeing Christ face to face.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Do you understand how the clouds are balanced — the wonders of the one who is perfect in knowledge (tĕmîm dēʿôṯ)?' The perfect knowledge is located in Christ: Col 2:3 'in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge.' The perfect knowledge Elihu claims imperfectly is Christ's actual possession — hidden in him for those who seek.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Why your clothes are warm when the earth lies still under the south wind?' The immediate bodily experience of divine care. Matt 6:28-30 'see how the flowers of the field grow... if that is how God clothes the grass of the field, will he not much more clothe you?' — Jesus points to the same mundane meteorological-botanical evidence of divine care, drawing the same theological conclusion Elihu implies.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Have you joined him in spreading out the sky (rāqîaʿ), firm and hard as a poured metal mirror?' The creation of the firmament. Prov 8:27 Wisdom was present 'when he set the heavens in place, when he marked out the horizon on the face of the deep.' Col 1:16 'all things in heaven and on earth... all things have been created through him and for him' — including the sky that Elihu describes Job as unable to have helped spread out.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The theme: 'Tell us what we should say to him — we cannot arrange our words because of our darkness.' Human darkness before God. The NT does not remove this darkness through better human speech but through divine provision: Rom 8:26 'the Spirit himself intercedes for us through wordless groans... the Spirit intercedes for God's people in accordance with the will of God.' Christ provides both the mediator (himself) and the helper (the Spirit) for the failure of human speech before God.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: 'Should he be told that I want to speak? Can anyone speak to him without being consumed?' The impossibility of unmediated human speech to God. 1 Tim 2:5 'there is one God and one mediator between God and mankind, the man Christ Jesus.' The consumption that Elihu fears — the creature consumed by divine presence — is what Christ prevents through his mediatorial work (Heb 9:14-15).</p>",
    "21": "<p>A revelation of God: 'People cannot look at the bright light in the clouds.' The divine inaccessibility. 1 Tim 6:16 God 'lives in unapproachable light, whom no one has seen or can see.' The same inaccessible light is what John 1:14 says 'became flesh and made his dwelling among us' — the unapproachable light becomes approachable in Christ. 2 Cor 4:6 'God, who said, &#8220;Let light shine out of darkness,&#8221; made his light shine in our hearts to give us the light of the knowledge of God&#8217;s glory displayed in the face of Christ.'</p>",
    "22": "<p>A revelation of God: 'From the north comes golden brightness; God comes in fearsome majesty (nôrāʾ hôḏ).' The divine approach from the north in golden light. Rev 4:3 'there was a rainbow that shone like an emerald encircling the throne'; Rev 21:11 the new Jerusalem 'shone with the glory of God, and its brilliance was like that of a very precious jewel.' The fearsome majesty Elihu perceives in the approaching storm is the glory that surrounds the enthroned Christ.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A revelation of God: 'As for the Almighty (Šaddai), we cannot reach him; he is great in power (ḵōaḥ), in justice (mišpāṭ), and in abundant righteousness (ṣĕḏāqāh).' The triple attribute is exactly Paul's doxology in Rom 11:33: 'the depth of the riches both of the wisdom and knowledge of God; how unsearchable his judgments and his paths beyond tracing out!' Phil 4:7 'the peace of God, which transcends all understanding.' The unreachable God is reached through Christ (Eph 2:13; 3:12).</p>",
    "24": "<p>A revelation of God: 'He does not attend to those who are wise in their own eyes.' God bypasses self-sufficient wisdom. 1 Cor 1:25-29 'God chose the foolish things of the world to shame the wise... not many of you were wise by human standards... but God chose the lowly things of this world and the despised things.' Christ's incarnation itself is the pattern: the Wisdom of God comes as a carpenter's son (Matt 13:54-57), bypassing those wise in their own eyes.</p>"
  },
  "38": {
    "1": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Then the LORD (YHWH) answered Job out of the whirlwind.' The return of the divine name YHWH — the first since the prose frame — marks the covenantal breakthrough. In Christ, YHWH speaks definitively and finally: Heb 1:1-2 'in the past God spoke to our ancestors through the prophets at many times and in various ways, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.' The whirlwind theophany is the OT form; the Incarnation is the NT reality. Acts 2:2 the Pentecost wind from heaven carries the same theophanic vocabulary.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who is this who clouds my purpose (ʿĕṣāh) with words that have no knowledge?' The divine counsel (ʿĕṣāh) that cannot be clouded is the eternal plan. Isa 46:10 'my purpose (ʿĕṣātî) will stand; I will do all that I please'; Eph 1:9-11 'the mystery of his will... the purpose of him who works out everything in conformity with the purpose of his will.' Christ is the agent of this eternal purpose (Eph 3:10-11 'according to his eternal purpose that he accomplished in Christ Jesus our Lord').</p>",
    "3": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Brace yourself like a man (ʾĕzor-nāʾ ḵĕḡeḇer); I will question you and you must answer me.' The divine challenge to stand. Rev 1:17 when John sees the glorified Christ, 'I fell at his feet as though dead. Then he placed his right hand on me and said: &#8220;Do not be afraid. I am the First and the Last.&#8221;' The divine challenge that reveals human inadequacy is met by the same Christ who then assures and restores the one who falls.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A direct anticipation: 'Where were you when I laid the earth's foundation?' Job was not there — but Christ was. Heb 1:10 quotes Ps 102:25 directly of Christ: 'In the beginning, Lord, you laid the foundations of the earth, and the heavens are the work of your hands.' Col 1:16 'all things have been created through him and for him. He is before all things.' The rhetorical question that diminishes Job's standing is answered by the pre-existent Son who stood with the Father at creation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who determined its measurements — do you know?' The precision of creation's dimensions. Prov 8:27-29 Wisdom was present 'when he marked out the horizon on the face of the deep, when he established the clouds above and fixed securely the fountains of the deep.' The measuring that YHWH challenges Job about is exactly the work that Christ as Wisdom performed (1 Cor 1:24 'Christ the power of God and the wisdom of God').</p>",
    "6": "<p>A direct anticipation: 'Who laid its cornerstone (ʾeḇen pinnāh)?' The cornerstone of creation has a NT referent. Ps 118:22 'the stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone' — applied to Christ in Matt 21:42; Acts 4:11; 1 Pet 2:6-7; Eph 2:20 'built on the foundation of the apostles and prophets, with Christ Jesus himself as the chief cornerstone.' The cosmological cornerstone that YHWH placed at creation is the same Christ who is the cornerstone of the new creation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: 'When the morning stars sang together and all the divine beings (bĕnê ʾĔlōhîm) shouted for joy?' The celestial court's joy at creation is fulfilled in the joy before the Lamb. Col 1:16 'whether thrones or powers or rulers or authorities; all things have been created through him and for him' — the morning stars and sons of God who shouted for joy at creation were themselves created by the pre-existent Christ. Rev 5:11-12 these same beings sing before the Lamb: 'worthy is the Lamb who was slain, to receive power and wealth and wisdom and strength and honor and glory and praise!'</p>",
    "8": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who shut in the sea with doors when it burst out from the womb?' Christ's sovereignty over the sea is the NT demonstration of his creatorial authority. Mark 4:39 'he rebuked the wind and said to the waves, &#8220;Quiet! Be still!&#8221; And the wind died down and it was completely calm.' Matt 8:27 'what kind of man is this? Even the winds and the waves obey him!' The disciples' question answers itself: the kind who was present when the sea burst out from the womb and set its bars and doors.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A revelation of God: 'When I made clouds its garment and thick darkness its swaddling cloth.' The newborn sea wrapped in divine garments — the Creator as cosmic midwife. Christ enters human birth wrapped in human swaddling clothes (Luke 2:7) — the Creator who swaddled the primordial sea is himself swaddled as an infant. The clothing of creation and the clothing of the Incarnation are both the Creator's acts of governance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A revelation of God: 'When I fixed its boundaries and set its bars and doors.' The ḥōq (statute/decree) for the sea — the same legal vocabulary as Sinai. The God who gave the Torah to Israel gave the sea its statute at creation; both are governance by the divine Word. John 1:1-3 'in the beginning was the Word... through him all things were made' — the statutes of creation and covenant are both the Word's work.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: 'This far you may come and no farther; here your proud waves will stop.' Fulfilled directly in the Gospels: Matt 8:26 Jesus 'rebuked the winds and the waves, and it was completely calm.' The disciples' awe ('what kind of man is this?') is the NT recognition that they are witnessing the Creator exercising original authority. The boundary set by YHWH at creation is enforced by Christ at sea — same authority, same word, same Lord.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Have you ever commanded the morning since your life began, or told the dawn where to take its place?' The daily renewal of morning as divine command. Matt 5:45 'he causes his sun to rise on the evil and the good' — Christ cites this to ground the command to love enemies: the Father's daily morning-governance is the model for impartial love. 2 Pet 1:19 'until the morning star rises in your hearts' — Christ himself is the final morning that his return brings.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A shadow: 'So that it would seize the earth's edges and shake the wicked out of it.' The morning-as-shaker removing the wicked is eschatological. Heb 12:26-27 'at that time his voice shook the earth, but now he has promised, &#8220;Once more I will shake not only the earth but also the heavens.&#8221; The words &#8220;once more&#8221; indicate the removing of what can be shaken.' Christ's return is the ultimate morning that shakes creation and removes everything that does not belong to the kingdom.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A revelation of God: 'The earth changes like clay under a seal; its features stand out like a garment.' The seal pressed into clay leaves the creator's impression. God's seal on the Son is explicitly mentioned in John 6:27: 'on him God the Father has placed his seal.' The earth bearing God's creative seal points to Christ as the one who bears the Father's seal — the one on whom the imprint of the Father's nature rests (Heb 1:3 'the exact representation of his being').</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: 'From the wicked their light is taken away, and the arm raised in violence shall be broken.' The removal of the wicked's light and power. John 1:5 'the light shines in the darkness, and the darkness has not overcome it.' The arm of violence that is broken is the Adversary's power: Heb 2:14 'so that by his death he might break the power of him who holds the power of death — that is, the devil.'</p>",
    "16": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Have you gone down to the springs of the sea, or walked through the depths of the abyss (tĕhôm)?' Christ descends to the depths. Phil 2:10 'in heaven and on earth and under the earth every knee should bow' — the under-the-earth dimension is Christ's descent. 1 Pet 3:18-19 'he was put to death in the body but made alive in the Spirit, through whom also he went and made proclamation to the imprisoned spirits.' Christ walks through the depths that Job has never seen.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A direct anticipation: 'Have the gates of death been revealed to you? Have you seen the doors of deepest darkness (ṣalmāwet)?' Job has not seen these gates; Christ holds their keys. Rev 1:18 'I am the Living One; I was dead, and now look, I am alive for ever and ever! And I hold the keys of death and Hades.' Matt 16:18 'the gates of Hades will not overcome it [my church].' The gates that YHWH asks Job if he has seen are the gates that Christ has passed through, conquered, and now controls.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Have you comprehended the earth's full breadth?' The spatial incomprehensibility of creation. Eph 3:18-19 'to grasp how wide and long and high and deep is the love of Christ, and to know this love that surpasses knowledge.' Paul applies spatial comprehension language to Christ's love — the breadth of the earth that Job cannot comprehend is surpassed by the breadth of Christ's love that Paul prays believers will grasp.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Where is the way to where light lives?' John 1:9 'the true light that gives light to everyone was coming into the world'; 1 John 1:5 'God is light; in him there is no darkness at all.' The dwelling-place of light is the divine nature itself. John 8:12 'I am the light of the world' — Christ is the answer to the cosmological question: he is where light lives, having taken on flesh to bring the light's dwelling into the created world.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: 'Can you take it to its territory and find the paths to its dwelling?' The inaccessibility of light's origin. The path to light's origin is Christ himself: John 14:6 'I am the way, the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.' The path to where light dwells — to the Father — is the Son. The unanswerable question in Job is answered by the Incarnation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A type (ironic): 'You know, of course — for you were born then, and the number of your days is very great!' The divine irony at Job's expense. But there is one who was 'born then' — Prov 8:22-25 'the LORD brought me forth as the first of his works... I was formed long ages ago, at the very beginning, when the world came to be'; John 8:58 'before Abraham was born, I am.' The one who was actually present at the foundation is Christ, whose 'days' are indeed very great — eternal.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Have you gone into the storehouses of the snow, or have you seen the storehouses of the hail?' The divine reserve of meteorological judgment. Rev 8:7 'there came hail and fire mixed with blood, and it was hurled down on the earth'; Rev 16:21 'hailstones weighing about a hundred pounds each fell from the sky on people.' The stored hail deployed in judgment is what Rev sees in Christ's eschatological return — the creation-storehouses finally opened.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Which I have kept in reserve for the time of trouble, for the day of battle and war.' The divine reserve for eschatological judgment. Rev 19:11-16 'I saw heaven standing open and there before me was a white horse, whose rider is called Faithful and True. With justice he judges and wages war... He is dressed in a robe dipped in blood, and his name is the Word of God.' The reserved arsenal deployed at creation's end is deployed by the returning Christ.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A revelation of God: 'By what path does the light divide, or the east wind scatter itself across the earth?' The east wind (qādîm) as divine instrument. Matt 24:27 'for as lightning that comes from the east is visible even in the west, so will be the coming of the Son of Man.' The east as the direction of divine approach connects the meteorological east wind to the eschatological direction of Christ's return.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who has cut a channel (pēleg) for the flood of waters, or a path for the thunderbolt?' The designed channels of rain and lightning. Ps 1:3 'like a tree planted by streams of water (palgê-māyim)' — the same channel-vocabulary; the channels of water that YHWH cut at creation become the channels of blessing that produce the righteous person's fruitfulness. John 7:38 'whoever believes in me, as Scripture has said, rivers of living water will flow from within them' — the channels of the Spirit.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A revelation of God: 'To bring rain on a land where no person lives, on the desert with no human in it.' God's care for the uninhabited. Luke 12:6 'are not five sparrows sold for two pennies? Yet not one of them is forgotten by God' — Jesus extends the same principle: the Father cares for what is beyond human observation or appreciation. The rain on uninhabited desert is evidence of a Creator whose care is not anthropocentric.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A revelation of God: 'To satisfy the desolate wasteland and make the tender grass spring up.' The watered desert as image of divine abundance. Isa 35:1-2 'the desert and the parched land will be glad; the wilderness will rejoice and blossom' — the Messianic transformation of desert to garden. John 4:14 'the water I give them will become in them a spring of water welling up to eternal life' — Christ brings the spring that makes the wasteland bloom.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Does the rain have a father? Who has fathered the drops of dew?' The Father-language for natural processes. Isa 9:6 'everlasting Father (ʾăḇî-ʿaḏ)' is a Messianic title for the coming child. The Father of rain is also the everlasting Father — both are functions of the same divine generativity that is expressed in Christ as eternal Son and applied to all creation.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A revelation of God: 'From whose womb did the ice come?' The birth-language for creation processes — ice born from a divine womb — is the complement to the male Father-of-rain imagery. Together they suggest that divine creativity transcends the gender categories it uses. Col 1:15 'the firstborn of all creation' — Christ's relation to creation is expressed in birth-language; he is born 'before all creation' as the Father's eternal Son.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A revelation of God: 'The waters harden like stone, and the surface of the deep is locked.' The frozen deep is the most remote and inaccessible part of creation. Christ descended into the lowest depths (Eph 4:9 'he also descended to the lower, earthly regions'; Phil 2:10 'under the earth'). The locked deep that YHWH challenges Job about is the depth that Christ has already entered and emerged from in the resurrection.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Can you bind the chains of the Pleiades, or can you release the belt of Orion?' The constellations under divine governance. Col 1:16-17 'whether thrones or powers or rulers or authorities... in him all things hold together' — the stars are among the 'all things' that hold together in Christ. Amos 5:8 'he who made the Pleiades and Orion, who turns midnight into dawn' — the same Creator who governs the stars is praised in both testaments.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Can you bring out Mazzaroth in its season? Can you guide the Bear with its cubs?' The seasonal guidance of constellations is part of the creation governance attributed to Christ: Heb 1:3 'sustaining all things by his powerful word.' The Bear guided through the seasons is held in the same Word by which Christ sustains all creation — from the largest constellation to the smallest sparrow (Matt 10:29).</p>",
    "33": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Do you know the laws of heaven (ḥuqqôṯ šāmayim)? Can you establish its rule over the earth?' The ḥuqqôṯ (statutes/laws) of the heavens parallel the Torah's ḥuqqîm — both are expressions of divine legislative authority. Matt 5:17 'do not think that I have come to abolish the Law or the Prophets; I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them.' Christ who fulfills the Torah is the same who established the laws of heaven — both are his word.</p>",
    "34": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Can you raise your voice to the clouds and make a flood of water come down?' The prayer-to-cloud motif. John 11:41-43: before raising Lazarus, Jesus prays and then commands — the Father answers immediately. John 12:28 'Father, glorify your name! Then a voice came from heaven: &#8220;I have glorified it, and will glorify it again.&#8221;' Christ's prayer is immediately answered by the Father — not because he has human power to command rain, but because the Father honors the Son's voice.</p>",
    "35": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Can you send out lightning bolts on commission, and do they report back to you: Here we are?' The lightning as obedient messenger. Ps 104:4 'he makes winds his messengers, flames of fire his servants' (quoted in Heb 1:7 of the angels). Rev 22:6 'the Lord, the God who inspires the prophets, sent his angel to show his servants the things that must soon take place.' Christ sends his messengers — angels, prophets, apostles — who report back; he commands the lightning as he commands his church.</p>",
    "36": "<p>A direct anticipation: 'Who has placed wisdom within the hidden self (ṭuḥôṯ)?' The inward wisdom planted by God. Jer 31:33 'I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts' — the New Covenant inward law. 1 Cor 2:10 'the Spirit searches all things, even the deep things of God'; 1 Cor 1:24 'Christ the power of God and the wisdom of God'; 1 Cor 1:30 'Christ Jesus... has become for us wisdom from God.' The wisdom hidden in the inner self is Christ himself, received through the Spirit's indwelling.</p>",
    "37": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who has the wisdom to count the clouds? Who can tilt the water jars of heaven?' The cloud-counting and water-jar wisdom. 2 Cor 4:7 'we have this treasure in jars of clay' — the vessel-of-water metaphor is applied to the gospel bearers; they carry the divine water of the Spirit in clay jars. The water jars of heaven that only God can tilt are the source; the clay jars of the apostles are the vessels for distributing what God pours out.</p>",
    "38": "<p>A revelation of God: 'When the dust hardens into a mass and the clods of dirt cling together?' The agricultural reality of drought-hardened soil. The soil that only rain can soften images the human heart that only the Spirit can soften (Ezek 36:26 'I will remove from you your heart of stone and give you a heart of flesh'). The same divine power that tips the water jars of heaven to soften the dust softens the hardened human heart.</p>",
    "39": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Do you hunt prey for the lion and fill the hunger of its cubs?' The divine provision for the apex predator. Matt 6:26 'look at the birds of the air; they do not sow or reap or store away in barns, and yet your heavenly Father feeds them.' If God provides for birds and lions — creatures of no soteriological significance — how much more for human beings? Christ draws the a fortiori argument: the Creator who feeds the lion feeds his people.</p>",
    "40": "<p>A revelation of God: 'When they crouch in their dens and wait in ambush in their thickets?' The lion's behavior as part of the divinely ordered predator-prey system. Rev 5:5 'see, the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has triumphed' — Christ himself is the Lion, the apex predator of the spiritual order. The crouching lion that YHWH feeds is, in the eschatological reversal, Christ himself — the Lion who conquers by being the Lamb.</p>",
    "41": "<p>A revelation of God: 'Who provides the raven its food when its chicks cry out to God and wander about hungry?' The raven's cry to God for food. Luke 12:24 'consider the ravens: they do not sow or reap, they have no storeroom or barn; yet God feeds them. And how much more valuable you are than birds!' Jesus's application of the raven-feeding to human anxiety is the direct NT drawing-out of what YHWH's cosmogonic question implies: the God who hears the raven's cry is the same who hears the believer's cry — and values the believer infinitely more.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'job')
    merge_comm(c, JOB3638)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'job', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in JOB3638.values())
    print(f'job mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 36–38')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
